"   <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H7594517\">",
"    <span class=\"h1\">",
"     SUMMARY AND RECOMMENDATIONS",
"    </span>",
"   </p>",
"   <p>",
"    <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"     <li>",
"      There are two forms of LAM. Pulmonary lymphangioleiomyomatosis (LAM) is a rare lung disease characterized pathologically by cyst formation and multifocal, nodular proliferation of immature smooth muscle and perivascular epithelioid cells (LAM cells). The majority of affected patients are young women of childbearing age. A very similar disease process is seen in approximately 30 percent of women with tuberous sclerosis complex (TSC). (See",
"      <a class=\"local\" href=\"#H1\">",
"       'Introduction'",
"      </a>",
"      above and",
"      <a class=\"medical medical_review\" href=\"UTD.htm?5/1/5142?source=see_link&amp;anchor=H2#H2\">",
"       \"Pulmonary involvement in tuberous sclerosis complex\", section on 'Clinical manifestations'",
"      </a>",
"      .)",
"     </li>",
"     <li>",
"      The pathogenesis of LAM is unknown, but may involve somatic mutations in one of the tuberous sclerosis genes, meaning that patients with LAM may have TSC-associated mutations in the lung (and sometimes the kidney) but not elsewhere. Another possibility is that estrogen supplementation participates in the development of clinically apparent LAM in genetically predisposed individuals. (See",
"      <a class=\"local\" href=\"#H5\">",
"       'Pathogenesis'",
"      </a>",
"      above and",
"      <a class=\"medical medical_review\" href=\"UTD.htm?33/38/34410?source=see_link&amp;anchor=H2#H2\">",
"       \"Tuberous sclerosis complex: Genetics, clinical features, and diagnosis\", section on 'Genetics'",
"      </a>",
"      .)",
"     </li>",
"     <li>",
"      Nearly all patients are symptomatic at presentation, and approximately 70 percent report dyspnea. (See",
"      <a class=\"local\" href=\"#H26516324\">",
"       'Symptoms and signs'",
"      </a>",
"      above.)",
"     </li>",
"     <li>",
"      Potential complications of LAM include pneumothorax, hemoptysis, chylothorax, chyloperitoneum, chylopericardium, and development of lymphangioleiomyomas of the lymph vessels. (See",
"      <a class=\"local\" href=\"#H7596701\">",
"       'Complications'",
"      </a>",
"      above.)",
"     </li>",
"     <li>",
"      High resolution computed tomography of the lung in LAM typically shows diffuse, homogeneous, small (less than one cm diameter) thin-walled cysts. Pleural nodules and complex masses may be seen in patients who have undergone prior thoracentesis, thoracoscopy, or pleurodesis. (See",
"      <a class=\"local\" href=\"#H9\">",
"       'Diagnosis'",
"      </a>",
"      above.)",
"     </li>",
"     <li>",
"      The diagnosis of pulmonary LAM may be strongly suggested by the clinical presentation and HRCT findings. (See",
"      <a class=\"local\" href=\"#H9\">",
"       'Diagnosis'",
"      </a>",
"      above.)",
"     </li>",
"     <li>",
"      No therapy is of proven benefit in pulmonary LAM, although studies of",
"      <a class=\"drug drug_general\" href=\"UTD.htm?5/39/5753?source=see_link\">",
"       sirolimus",
"      </a>",
"      are promising. LAM management is aimed at easing symptoms and preventing complications. (See",
"      <a class=\"local\" href=\"#H7596707\">",
"       'Management'",
"      </a>",
"      above.)",
"     </li>",
"     <li>",
"      Because of progressive respiratory failure, patients with LAM may eventually require lung transplantation. Selection criteria and outcomes are similar to those for other chronic lung diseases. (See",
